exercise.solution:

The components of \overrightarrow{PQ} are the difference of the respective components of the point Q and of the point P. Therefore,

	\overrightarrow{PQ}
	= 
	\begin{bmatrix} 
		5 - 2\\
		-2 - 0\\
		1-4
	\end{bmatrix} 
	= 
	\begin{bmatrix} 
		3\\
		-2\\
		-3
	\end{bmatrix} 
	.

Similarly,

	\overrightarrow{QP}
	= 
	\begin{bmatrix} 
		2-5\\
		0-(-2) \\
		4-1
	\end{bmatrix} 
	= 
	\begin{bmatrix} 
		-3\\
		2\\
		3
	\end{bmatrix} 
	.

Notice that \overrightarrow{PQ} = (-1)\overrightarrow{QP}.

exercise.statement:

(Source: , Section 4.1, Exercise 4.1.10)
							In each case, find a point Q such that \overrightarrow{PQ} has
							

the same direction as \mathbf{v};
								

the opposite direction of \mathbf{v}.
															  
							
							


									P=(-1,2,2), \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}		
								


								 	P=(3,0,-1), \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}

exercise.solution:
							First, recall that the vector \vect{PQ} can be computed as
							
								\vect{PQ} = \vect{OQ}-\vect{OP},
								\text{ where } O \text{ denotes the origin.}
							
							Since we are looking for a point Q, we should rephrase this equation:
							
								\vect{OQ} = \vect{OP} + \vect{PQ}.
							
							Secondly, recall that \vect{PQ} has the same (resp. the opposite) direction of \mbf{v} if \vect{PQ} = c \mbf{v} for some positive (resp. negative) real number c. Plugging this back into , we see that we would like Q to satisfy
							
								\vect{OQ} = \vect{OP} + c\mbf{v} 
							
							for some positive (resp. negative) number c.
							Therefore, we should compute \vect{OP}+\mbf{v} (resp. \vect{OP}-\mbf{v}) for the given point P and the given vector \mbf{v}.Notice that we could also compute \vect{OP}+5\mbf{v}, \vect{OP}+ \pi \mbf{v}, or many other things for , but the positive number +1 is an easy choice. Similarly, for , we could also compute \vect{OP}-5\mbf{v}, \vect{OP} - \frac{1}{8} \mbf{v}, etc. - there are many correct answers.
							

First, our solution for 
								P=(-1,2,2) and \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}:


							same direction:
								We compute

								
									\vect{OP}+\mbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}  
									+
									\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -1+1 \\ 2+3 \\ 2+1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  0 \\ 5 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}  
									.
								

								We have argued before that this should equal \vect{OQ}, so we conclude:
								
									Q = (0 , 5 , 3).
								
								Let us check our solution: we have

								
									\vect{PQ}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  0 \\ 5 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}  
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}  -1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  0-(-1) \\ 5-2 \\ 3-2 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\mbf{v},
								

								so that \vect{PQ} indeed has the same direction as \mbf{v} (since they are equal).
							


							opposite direction:
								We compute

								
									\vect{OP}-\mbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}  
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -1-1 \\ 2-3 \\ 2-1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -2 \\ -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}  
									.
								

								We have argued before that this should equal \vect{OQ}, so we conclude:
								
									Q = (-2 , -1 , 1).
								
								Let us check our solution: we have

								
									\vect{PQ}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -2 \\ -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}  
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}  -1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -2-(-1) \\ -1-2 \\ 1-2 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -1 \\ -3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									(-1)
									\mbf{v},
								

								so that \vect{PQ} indeed has the opposite direction as \mbf{v}.
									
							

Next, our solution for P=(3,0,-1) and \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} :


							same direction:
								We compute

								
									\vect{OP}+\mbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  3 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}  
									+
									\begin{bmatrix}  2 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  3+2 \\ 0+(-1) \\ -1+3 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  5 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}  
									.
								

								We have argued before that this should equal \vect{OQ}, so we conclude:
								
								
									Q = (5 , -1 , 2).
								
								
								
								Let us check our solution: we have
								
								
									\vect{PQ}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  5 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}  
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}  3 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  5-3 \\ -1-0 \\ 2-(-1) \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  2 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\mbf{v},
								
								
								so that \vect{PQ} indeed has the same direction as \mbf{v} (since they are equal).
							


							opposite direction:
									
								We compute
								
								
									\vect{OP}-\mbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  3 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}  
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}  2 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  3-2 \\ 0-(-1) \\ -1-3 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 1 \\ -4 \end{bmatrix}  
									.
								
								
								We have argued before that this should equal \vect{OQ}, so we conclude:
								
								
									Q = (1 , 1 , -4).
								
								
								Let us check our solution: we have
								
								
									\vect{PQ}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 1 \\ -4\end{bmatrix}  
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}  3 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  1-3 \\ 1-0 \\ -4-(-1) \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  -2 \\ 1 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}  
									=
									(-1)
									\mbf{v},
								
								
								so that \vect{PQ} indeed has the opposite direction as \mbf{v}.

							In the following, let \mbf{r} be the vector of the point R. In other words,
								
									\mbf{r}
									=
									\mbf{p}+\mbf{q}
								
							by the choice of R.
							 


									By definition, the components of \overrightarrow{QP} are the difference of the respective components of the point P and of the point Q, or in other words:
									
										\overrightarrow{QP}
										=
										\mbf{p}-\mbf{q}.
										
								



Similarly, we have


									
										\overrightarrow{QR}
										=
										\mbf{r}-\mbf{q}
										=
										(\mbf{p}+\mbf{q}) -\mbf{q}
										=
										\mbf{p}.
									
									
								



Just as above, we have


									
										\overrightarrow{RP}
										=
										\mbf{p}-\mbf{r}
										=
										\mbf{p}-(\mbf{p}+\mbf{q})
										=
										-\mbf{q}.
									
																
								



If we write \mbf{0} for the vector of the origin O, all of whose components are zero, then	


									
										\overrightarrow{RO}
										=
										\mbf{0} - \mbf{r}
										=
										- (\mbf{p}+\mbf{q})
										=
										-\mbf{p} - \mbf{q}.

exercise.hint:
Vector addition is defined componentwise. For example,

	\begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}
	+
	\begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} 
	=
	\begin{bmatrix} 5+(-2) \\ 6+3 \end{bmatrix} 
	=
	\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix} 
	.

exercise.solution:
By definition of vector addition, we have to add the numbers componentwise, so:

	\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
	+
	\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 5 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
	+
	\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ -4 \end{bmatrix} 
	=
	\begin{bmatrix}  1+1+(-1) \\ 2+5+2 \\ 3+1+(-4) \end{bmatrix} 
	=
	\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 9 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 	
	.

