exercise.statement:
(Source: , from Section 2.3, Exercise 2.2.2.) Use the properties of vector addition to show the following equalities. Justify every step.
(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})+\mathbf{w} =(\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w})+\mathbf{u}
(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{0})+(\mathbf{v}+(-\mathbf{u})) =\mathbf{v}.

exercise.hint:
Recall the properties of vector addition: for any vectors \mbf{x}, \mbf{y}, \mbf{z} with the same number of components, and c,d any real numbers, we have

	
		\text{Associativity:}
		\amp\amp
		\mbf{x} + (\mbf{y} + \mbf{z})
		\amp =
		(\mbf{x} + \mbf{y}) + \mbf{z}
	
	
		\text{Commutativity:}
		\amp\amp
		\mbf{x} + \mbf{y} 
		\amp =
		\mbf{y} + \mbf{x}
	
	
		\text{Neutral element } \mbf{0} \text{ of addition}:
		\amp\amp
		\mbf{0} + \mbf{x}
		\amp =
		\mbf{x}
	
	
		\text{Existence of inverse elements:} 
		\amp\amp
		\mbf{x} + (-\mbf{x})
		\amp =
		\mbf{0}
	

	
		\text{Identity of scalar multiplication:}
		\amp\amp
		1\mbf{x}
		\amp =
		\mbf{x}
	
	
		\text{Compatibility:}
		\amp\amp
		c(d\mbf{x})
		\amp =
		(cd)\mbf{x}
	
	
		\text{Distributivity 1:}
		\amp\amp
		c(\mbf{x} + \mbf{y})
		\amp =
		c\mbf{x} + c\mbf{y}
	
	
		\text{Distributivity 2:}
		\amp\amp
		(c+d)\mbf{x}
		\amp =
		c\mbf{x} + d\mbf{x}

exercise.statement:
(Source: , from Section 2.3, Exercise 2.3.3.) Use the properties of vector addition to show the following equalities, where k, l are scalars. Justify every step.
(k+l)(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v}) = k \mathbf{u} +k \mathbf{v} + l\mathbf{u} + l \mathbf{v}.
0 \mathbf{u} = \mathbf{0}
(-1)\mathbf{u} =-\mathbf{u}
-(k\mathbf{u}) = k(-\mathbf{u}) =(-k)\mathbf{u}

ol.li:
 		We have to show that (-1)\mathbf{u} behaves like the inverse elements -\mathbf{u} whose existence is claimed in  this axiom. In other words, it suffices to show that
 		
 			\mbf{u} + (-1)\mbf{u}
 			=
 			\mbf{0}.
 		 		
 		We compute:
 		
	 		
	 			\mbf{u} + (-1)\mbf{u}
		 		\amp =
		 		1\mbf{u} + (-1)\mbf{u}
		 		\amp (Identity of scalar multiplication)
		 	
		 	
		 		\amp =
		 		(1+ (-1))\mbf{u}
		 		\amp (Distributivity 2)
		 	
		 	
		 		\amp =
		 		0\mbf{u}
		 		\amp
		 	
		 	
		 		\amp =
		 		\mathbf{0}
		 		\amp ()

exercise.statement:
(Source: , from Section 4.1, Exercise 4.1.11.) Let \mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} , \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} , and \mathbf{w} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} . In each case, find \mathbf{x} such that:
3(2\mathbf{u}+ \mathbf{x}) + \mathbf{w} = 2\mathbf{x} -\mathbf{v}
2(3\mathbf{v}- \mathbf{x}) = 5\mathbf{w} +\mathbf{u} - 3\mathbf{x}.

exercise.solution:
							We will make extensive use of the axioms of vector addition and the things we have proved in .
							 




										
											\amp\amp
											3(2\mathbf{u}+ \mathbf{x}) + \mathbf{w}
											\amp
											= 2\mathbf{x} -\mathbf{v}
											\amp
										
										
											\iff \amp\amp
											6\mathbf{u}+ 3\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{w}
											\amp
											= 2\mathbf{x} -\mathbf{v}
											\amp
										
										
											\iff \amp\amp
											6\mathbf{u}+ 3\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{w} - 2\mathbf{x}
											\amp
											= 2\mathbf{x} -\mathbf{v} - 2\mathbf{x}
											\amp
											(-2\mathbf{x} \text{ on both sides})
										
										
											\iff \amp\amp
											6\mathbf{u}+ 1\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{w}
											\amp
											= -\mathbf{v}
											\amp
											
										
										
											\iff \amp\amp
											\mathbf{x}
											\amp
											= -\mathbf{v}- 6\mathbf{u}  -\mathbf{w}
											\amp
											
										
									

Using that


										
											-6\mathbf{u}
											=
											(-6)
											\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} (-6)3 \\ (-6)(-1) \\ (-6)0 \end{bmatrix} 
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} -18 \\ 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
										
									

and so forth, we can now just plug in the values in the equation for \mbf{x}:


										
											\mathbf{x}
											=
											-\mathbf{v}- 6\mathbf{u}  -\mathbf{w}
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} 
											+
											\begin{bmatrix} (-6)3 \\ (-6)(-1) \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
											+
											\begin{bmatrix} (-1)(-1) \\ (-1)1 \\ (-1)5 \end{bmatrix} 
										
										
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} -4+(-18)+1 \\ 0+6+(-1) \\ -1+0+(-5) \end{bmatrix} 
										
										
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} -21 \\ 5 \\ -6 \end{bmatrix} 
										
									
								



First, we compute:


										
											\amp\amp
											2(3\mathbf{v}- \mathbf{x})
											\amp =
											5\mathbf{w} +\mathbf{u} - 3\mathbf{x}
										
										
											\iff\amp\amp
											6\mathbf{v} - 2\mathbf{x}
											\amp =
											5\mathbf{w} +\mathbf{u} - 3\mathbf{x}
										
										
											\iff\amp\amp
											- 2\mathbf{x}+3\mathbf{x}
											\amp =
											5\mathbf{w} +\mathbf{u}-6\mathbf{v}
										
										
											\iff\amp\amp
											\mathbf{x}
											\amp =
											5\mathbf{w} +\mathbf{u}-6\mathbf{v}
										
									

Plugging in the vectors, we get:


									
										\mathbf{x}
										\amp =
										5\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} 
										+\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
										-6\begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
									
									
										\amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} -5 \\ 5 \\ 25 \end{bmatrix} 
										+\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
										+\begin{bmatrix} -24 \\ 0 \\ -6 \end{bmatrix} 
									
									
										\amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} -5+3-24 \\ 5-1+0 \\ 25+0-6 \end{bmatrix} 
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} -26 \\ 4 \\ 19 \end{bmatrix}

exercise.statement:
 (Source: , from Section 2.4, Exercise 2.4.2.) 
							Decide whether 
							
								\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 4\\ 4 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} 
							
							is a linear combination of the vectors
							
								\mathbf{u}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 3\\ 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} 
								\text{ and }
								\mathbf{u}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2\\ -2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} .


 (Source: , from Section 2.4, Exercise 2.4.2.) 
							Decide whether
							
								\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 4\\ 4 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
							
							is a linear combination of the vectors
							
								\mathbf{u_1} = \begin{bmatrix} 3\\ 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} ,
								\mathbf{u_2} = \begin{bmatrix} 8\\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}  
								\text{ and }
								\mathbf{u_3} = \begin{bmatrix} 2\\ -2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} .

 (Source: , Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.1.) 
							Compute \mathbf{u \cdot v}  where:
							


									\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 3\end{bmatrix} 
									and
									\mathbf{v} =  \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
								


									\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -1\end{bmatrix} 
									and
									\mathbf{v} =  \mathbf{u}.
								


									\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ -3\end{bmatrix} 
									and
									\mathbf{v} =  \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
								


									\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 5\end{bmatrix} 
									and
									\mathbf{v} =  \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix} 
								


									\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z\end{bmatrix} 
									and
									\mathbf{v} =  \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{bmatrix} 
								


									\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z\end{bmatrix} 
									and
									\mathbf{v} =  0

exercise.solution:
							Recall: the dot product of two vectors is the sum of the product of the components. 
							


									
										
											\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{v}
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 3\end{bmatrix} 
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
											=
											2\cdot (-1) + (-1)\cdot 1 + 3\cdot 1
											=
											-2 -1+3
											=
											0.
										
									
								


									
										
											\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{v}
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -1\end{bmatrix} 
											\cdot 
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -1\end{bmatrix} 	
											=
											1\cdot 1 + 2\cdot 2 + (-1)\cdot (-1)
											=
											1+4+1
											=
											6.
										
									
								


									
										
											\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{v}
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ -3\end{bmatrix} 
											\cdot 
											\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 	
											=
											1\cdot 2 + 1\cdot (-1) + (-3)\cdot 1
											=
											2-1-3=-2
										
									
								


									
										
											\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{v}
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 5\end{bmatrix} 
											\cdot 
											\begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix} 
											=
											3\cdot 6 + (-1)\cdot (-7)+5\cdot(-5)
											
										
											\amp =
											18 + 7 -25
											=
											0.
										
									
								


									
										
											\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{v}
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z\end{bmatrix} 
											\cdot 
											\begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{bmatrix} 
											=
											x\cdot a + y\cdot b + z\cdot c.
										
									
								


									
										
											\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{v}
											\amp =
											\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z\end{bmatrix} 
											\cdot 
											\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
											=
											x\cdot 0 + y\cdot 0 + z\cdot 0
											=
											0 + 0 + 0 = 0.

exercise.statement:

 (Source: , Section 4.1, Exercise 4.1.1.) 
							Compute \norm{\mathbf{v}} if \mathbf{v} equals:						 
						 	


									\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 2\end{bmatrix} 	
							 	


									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \\ 2\end{bmatrix} 
							 	


									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -1\end{bmatrix} 	
							 	


									\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 0 \\ 2\end{bmatrix} 	
							 	


									2\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \\ 2\end{bmatrix} 
							 	


