exercise.hint:
Definition: The norm \norm{\mathbf{v}} of a vector \mbf{v} is defined as

	\norm{\mathbf{v}}
	=
	\sqrt{\mbf{v}\cdot \mbf{v}}
	.

exercise.statement:

 (Source: , Section 4.1, Exercise 4.1.2.) 
							Find a unit vector in the direction of:		 	
						 	


									\begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ -1 \\ 5\end{bmatrix} 	
						 		


									\begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ -1 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}

exercise.solution:
							We need to find the length of the vector between the points.
							


									For P=( 3  ,  -1  ,  0) and  Q=( 2  ,  -1  ,  1 ), we compute:
									
										\vect{PQ}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											2-3 \\ -1-(-1) \\ 1-0 \end{bmatrix} 
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											-1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
										.
									
									Therefore,
									
										\norm{\vect{PQ}}
										=
										\sqrt{(-1)^2 + 0^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{2}.
									
								

For P=( 2  ,  -1  ,  2) and  Q=( 2  ,  0  ,  1), we compute:
									
										\vect{PQ}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											2-2 \\ 0-(-1) \\ 1-2 \end{bmatrix} 
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											0 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} 
										.
									
									Therefore,
									
										\norm{\vect{PQ}}
										=
										\sqrt{0^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2} = \sqrt{2}.
									
								


									For P=( -3 ,  5  ,  2) and  Q=( 1  ,  3  ,  3 ), we compute:
									
										\vect{PQ}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											1-(-3) \\ 3-5 \\ 3-2 \end{bmatrix} 
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											4 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
										.
									
									Therefore,
									
										\norm{\vect{PQ}}
										=
										\sqrt{4^2 + 2^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{21}.
									
								


									For P=( 4  ,  0  ,  -2) and  Q=( 3  ,  2  ,  0 ), we compute:
									
										\vect{PQ}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											3-4 \\ 2-0 \\ 0-(-2) \end{bmatrix} 
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 
											-1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
										.
									
									Therefore,
									
										\norm{\vect{PQ}}
										=
										\sqrt{(-1)^2 + 2^2 + 2^2} = \sqrt{9}=3.
									
								 
							
							We should point out that, in each of the above cases, we could just as well have computed \norm{\vect{QP}} and would have gotten the same result.

exercise.statement:

 (Source: , Section 2.6, Exercise 2.6.4.) 
							Find \cos(\theta) where \theta is the angle between the vectors
							
								\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} 
								\;\text{ and }\;									
								\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 4 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}


 (Source: , Section 4.7, Exercise 4.7.9.) 
							Find the angle between the vectors
								
									\mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
									\;\text{ and }\;
									\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -7 \end{bmatrix}


 (Source: , Section 4.7, Exercise 4.7.10.) 
							Find the \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{w}) where
								 \mathbf{w} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} , \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}

exercise.solution:
Since

	\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{w})
	=
	\left(
		\frac{\mbf{v}\cdot \mbf{w}}{\mbf{v}\cdot \mbf{v}}
	\right)
	\mbf{v}
	,

we should first compute the dot products:

	
		\mbf{v}\cdot \mbf{w}
		\amp =
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} 
		\cdot
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} 
		=
		1\cdot 1 + 2\cdot 0 + 3\cdot (-2)
		=
		-5,
	
	
		\mbf{v}\cdot \mbf{v}
		\amp =
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} 
		\cdot
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} 
		=
		1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2
		=
		14,
		\text{ and so }
	
	
		\amp \frac{\mbf{v}\cdot \mbf{w}}{\mbf{v}\cdot \mbf{v}}
		=
		\frac{-5}{14}
		.
	

Therefore,

	\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}}(\mathbf{w})
	=
	\frac{-5}{14}
	\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} 
	=
	\mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{-5}{14} \\ \frac{-10}{14} \\ \frac{-15}{14} \end{bmatrix} 
	.

exercise.statement:

 (Source: , Section 2.6, Exercise 2.6.14.) 
							Decompose the vector \mathbf{v} into \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b} where \mathbf{a} is parallel to \mathbf{u} and \mathbf{b} is perpendicular to \mathbf{u}.		
								 \mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -5 \end{bmatrix} , \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}

exercise.solution:
We require \mbf{a} to be parallel to \mbf{u}, i.e. \mbf{a} = c \mbf{u} for some real number c that is yet to be determined. Plugging that into \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}, we get a definition of \mbf{b} that also depends on c: \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{v} - c \mbf{u}. As \mbf{b} needs to be orthogonal to \mbf{u}, we want \mbf{b}\cdot \mbf{u}=0. If we plug our tentative solution for \mbf{b} into this, we get

	(\mathbf{v} - c \mbf{u})\cdot \mbf{u}=0
	.

Using the properties of the dot product, we arrive at

	\mathbf{v}\cdot \mbf{u} = c \mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{u},
	\text{ i.e. }
	c = \frac{\mathbf{v}\cdot \mbf{u}}{\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{u}}
	\text{ using that }\mbf{u}\neq \mbf{0}
	.

We can now compute both sides and get a value for c:

	
		\mathbf{v}\cdot \mbf{u}
		\amp =
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
		\cdot
		\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -5 \end{bmatrix} 
		=
		1\cdot 3 + (-1)\cdot 2 + 2\cdot (-5)
		=
		-9,
	
	
		\mbf{u}\cdot \mbf{u}
		\amp =
		\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -5 \end{bmatrix}
		\cdot
		\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -5 \end{bmatrix}
		=
		3^2 + 2^2 + (-5)^2
		=
		38, \text{ so that }
	


	c
	=
	\frac{-9}{38}.

We can now solve for our vectors \mbf{a} and \mbf{b}:

	
		\mbf{a} = c \mbf{u}	= \frac{-9}{38}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -5 \end{bmatrix} 
		=
		\begin{bmatrix} \frac{-27}{38} \\ \frac{-18}{38}\\ \frac{45}{38}\end{bmatrix} 
	
	
		\mathbf{b}
		=
		\mathbf{v} - \mbf{a}
		=
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
		-
		\begin{bmatrix} \frac{-27}{38} \\ \frac{-18}{38}\\ \frac{45}{38}\end{bmatrix} 
		=
		\begin{bmatrix} \frac{65}{38} \\ \frac{-20}{38}\\ \frac{31}{38}\end{bmatrix} 
		.
	

Let us do a sanity check: Is our \mbf{b} indeed orthogonal to \mbf{u}? We compute:

	
		\mbf{b}\cdot \mbf{u}
		\amp =
		\begin{bmatrix} \frac{65}{38} \\ \frac{-20}{38}\\ \frac{31}{38}\end{bmatrix} 
		\cdot
		\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -5 \end{bmatrix} 
	=
		\frac{65}{38} \cdot 3 + \frac{-20}{38}\cdot 2 + \frac{31}{38}\cdot (-5)
	
	
		\amp =
		\frac{195-40-155}{38}
		=
		0,
	

so yes!

							First, let us draw the triangle as suggested by the hint:


							 
									A triangle with \mathbf{u} and \mathbf{v} as two sides 
									
									
										\begin{tikzpicture}[line cap=round, line join=round, >=triangle 45, x=1.0cm,y=1.0cm]
										\begin{axis}[
											anchor=origin,  % Align the origins
											x=1cm, y=1cm, % Set the same unit vectors
											hide axis
													]
												\addplot [-latex] table {
													0 0
													1 2
													}
											node[near end, above] {\scriptsize $\mathbf{u}$};
													\addplot [-latex] table {
													0 0
													3 1
													} node[near end, below] {\scriptsize $\mathbf{v}$};
											\end{axis}
											\end{tikzpicture}

							To show that a parallelogram is a rectangle, we need to see that the enclosed angles are 90^\circ. If we think of two adjacent sides of the parallelogram as vectors \mbf{x} and \mbf{y}, then its other two sides are translates of  \mbf{x} and \mbf{y}, as depicted in :


							 
									A parallelogram with \mbf{x} and \mbf{y} as two adjacent sides 
									
									
										\begin{tikzpicture}[line cap=round, line join=round, >=triangle 45, x=1.0cm,y=1.0cm, scale=0.5]
										\begin{axis}[
											anchor=origin,  % Align the origins
											x=2cm, y=2cm, % Set the same unit vectors
											hide axis
													]
											\addplot [-latex] table {
													0 0
													1 2
													}
											node[left] {\scriptsize $\mbf{x}$};
													\addplot [-latex] table {
													0 0
													3 1
													} node[below] {\scriptsize $\mbf{y}$};
											\addplot [-latex] table {
													3 1
													4 3
													}
											node[right] {\scriptsize $\mbf{x}$};
											\addplot [-latex] table {
													1 2
													4 3
													} node[above] {\scriptsize $\mbf{y}$};
											\end{axis}
											\end{tikzpicture}
									
								
							
							
							We now see that the two diagonals can be described by the vectors \mbf{x}+\mbf{y} and \mbf{x} - \mbf{y}:


							 
									The diagonals of the parallelogram from   
									
									
										\begin{tikzpicture}[line cap=round, line join=round, >=triangle 45, x=0.5cm,y=0.5cm]
										\begin{axis}[
											anchor=origin,  % Align the origins
											x=2cm, y=2cm, % Set the same unit vectors
											hide axis
													]
											\addplot [-, gray, ultra thin] table {
													0 0
													1 2
													};
											\addplot [-, gray, ultra thin] table {
													0 0
													3 1
													};
											\addplot [-, gray, ultra thin] table {
													3 1
													4 3
													};
											\addplot [-, gray, ultra thin] table {
													1 2
													4 3
													};
											\addplot [-latex] table {
													3 1
													1 2
													} node[near end] {\scriptsize $\mbf{x}-\mbf{y}$};
											\addplot [-latex] table {
													0 0
													4 3
													} node[near end] {\scriptsize $\mbf{x}+\mbf{y}$};
											\end{axis}
											\end{tikzpicture}
									
								
							
							
							If we assume that our parallelogram's diagonals have the same length, then by the above argument, that means that \norm{\mbf{x}+\mbf{y}} = \norm{\mbf{x}-\mbf{y}}. We can therefore apply  to the vectors \mbf{u}:= \mbf{x}+\mbf{y} and \mbf{v}:= \mbf{x} - \mbf{y}: Since \norm{\mbf{u}} = \norm{\mbf{v}}, we conclude that \mbf{u} + \mbf{v} and \mbf{u} - \mbf{v} are orthogonal. Plugging in the definition of \mbf{u} and \mbf{v}, this means that
							
								(\mbf{x}+\mbf{y}) + (\mbf{x} - \mbf{y}) 
								=								
								2\mbf{x}
							
							and
							
								(\mbf{x}+\mbf{y}) - (\mbf{x} - \mbf{y})
								=
								2\mbf{y}
							
							are orthogonal, and therefore, so are  \mbf{x} and \mbf{y}. Since twp adjacent sides of the parallelogram are orthogonal, it is a rectangle.

