									 				1-2 \\ 1-1 \\ 1-0
										 		\end{bmatrix} 
										 		=
										 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				-1 \\ 0 \\ 1
										 		\end{bmatrix} 			 		
										 	

gives the direction of said line.

The vector equation of the line in question is therefore given by


									 		\mbf{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			2 \\ -1 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			-1 \\ 0 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 	

The parametric form is therefore given by


											x_1 = 2-t
											;
											x_2 = -1
											;
											x_3 = 1+t
											.
										
										
								 	
								 	

Vector equation:


									 		\mbf{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			2 \\ -1 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			-1 \\ 0 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 	

Parametric form:


											x_1 = 2-t
											;
											x_2 = -1
											;
											x_3 = 1+t
										
										
									
								
							 	



The lines through P=(1,0,1) that meet the line \ell whose vector equation is given by \mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}  +t \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1\\ 2 \end{bmatrix}  at points with distance 3 from Q=(1,2,0).


								 	
							 		

First, let us find the points R on \ell that have distance 3 from Q: Having distance 3 means exactly that
								 		


								 			\norm{ \vect{QR} } = 3.
								 		

The fact that R is on \ell means that, for some real number t, we have


								 			\vect{OR} = 
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			+
								 			t
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 		

Thus,


								 			\vect{QR} = 
								 			\left(
									 			\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
									 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 			+
									 			t
									 			\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
									 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			\right)
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1\\2\\0
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2t \\ -t\\ 2t
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 		

and we therefore want


								 			\norm{ \begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2t \\ -t\\ 2t
								 			\end{bmatrix} } = 3,
								 			\text{ i.e. }
								 			(2t)^2 + (-t)^2 + (2t)^2 = 9.
								 		

This means, we need 9t^2=9, or in other words, t=\pm 1. Therefore, there are two points R_+, R_- on \ell which have distance 3 from Q, namely the points that satisfy


								 			\vect{O R_+} = 
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			+
								 			1
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				3 \\ 1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 		

and


								 			\vect{OR_-} = 
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			1
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-1 \\ 3\\ -2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			.
								 		

Any line through P can be described by the vector equation 


									 		\mbf{x}
									 		=
									 		\vect{OP}
									 		+
									 		s
									 		\mbf{d}
									 	

for some directional vector \mbf{d}. For our line to go through R_+, we need to choose


									 		\mbf{d}
									 		=
									 		\vect{PR_+}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				3 \\ 1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ 1\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 		

and the vector equation for this line is then given by 


									 		\mbf{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		s
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ 1\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			.
									 	

Its parametric form is therefore given by


											x_1 = 1+2s
											;
											x_2 = s
											;
											x_3 = 1+s
											.
										
										

For the line to go through R_- on the other hand, we need to choose


									 		\mbf{d}
									 		=
									 		\vect{PR_-}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-1 \\ 3\\ -2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-2 \\ 3\\ -3
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 		

and the vector equation for this line is then given by 


									 		\mbf{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		s
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-2 \\ 3\\ -3
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			.
									 	

Its parametric form is then given by


											x_1 = 1-2s
											;
											x_2 = 3s
											;
											x_3 = 1-3s
											.
										
										
								 	
								 	
								 		There are two lines that meet the given line at distance 3 from Q and go through P:

Vector equation of the first line:


									 		\mbf{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ 1\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix}
									 	

Parametric form of the first line:


											x_1 = 1+2t
											;
											x_2 = t
											;
											x_3 = 1+t
										
										

Vector equation of the second line:


									 		\mbf{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-2 \\ 3\\ -3
								 			\end{bmatrix}
									 	

Parametric form of the second line:


											x_1 = 1-2t
											;
											x_2 = 3t
											;
											x_3 = 1-3t
											.


 (Source: , Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.14.) 
							Find the normal, general, and parametric form of each of the following planes.					
							
							To find a vector in \mathbb{R}^3 that is normal to a plane, you need to find two non-parallel vectors \mbf{a} and \mbf{b} in the plane and compute their cross product
							
								\mbf{a}\times \mbf{b}
								=
								\begin{bmatrix}
									a_2b_3-a_3b_2\\
									a_3b_1-a_1b_3\\
									a_1b_2-a_2b_1
								\end{bmatrix}
							
							where a_i, b_i are the three components of \mbf{a} resp. \mbf{b}. This vector is orthogonal to both \mbf{a} and \mbf{b} and hence normal to the plane.
						
						
							In order to determine the normal form of a plane, you need both a single point P on the plane and a normal vector \mbf{n} to the plane. Then, any point X=(x_1,x_2,x_3) on the plane can be described by the normal form \mbf{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0. 
						
					 	  



Passing through A=(2,1,3),  B=(1,1,3), and C=(1,2,-3).


					 				

To find a normal vector \mbf{n}, we need two non-parallel vectors in the plane; for example, the two vectors


					 						\vect{AB}
					 						=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				3 \\ -1\\ 5
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 1\\ 3
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -2\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 		

and


					 						\vect{AC}
					 						=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 2\\ -3
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 1\\ 3
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				0 \\ 1 \\ -6
								 			\end{bmatrix}								 			
					 					

would do. (If these two vectors had turned out to be parallel, then the three given points A, B, C would lie on a line, so they would not determine a plane.) A vector \mbf{n} which is orthogonal to both \vect{AB} and \vect{AC} is then given by their cross product (see ):


					 						\mbf{n}
					 						=
					 						\vect{AB}
					 						\times
					 						\vect{AC}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 (-2) \cdot (-6) - 2 \cdot 1 \\
											 2 \cdot 0 - 2 \cdot (-6) \\
											 2 \cdot 1 - (-2)\cdot  0
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 10 \\
											 12 \\
											 2
											\end{bmatrix}
											.
					 					

The normal form, \mbf{n}\cdot\vect{AX}=0, is now explicitly given by


					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 10 \\
											 12 \\
											 2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				x_1 - 1 \\ x_2 - 1\\ x_3 -3
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
											0
					 					

or equivalently


					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 10 \\
											 12 \\
											 2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\mbf{x}
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix}
											 10 \\
											 12 \\
											 2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 1\\ 3
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			=
								 			28
								 			.
					 					

We get the general form by simply computing the dot product on both sides:


					 						10x_1
					 						+
											12x_2
											+
											2x_3
											=
											28.
					 					

Lastly, we compute the parametric form by first giving the vector form:


					 						\mbf{x}
					 						=
					 						\vect{OA}
					 						+t\vect{AB}
					 						+s\vect{AC}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 1\\ 3
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
					 						+t\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -2\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
					 						+s
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				0 \\ 1 \\ -6
								 			\end{bmatrix}.
								 		

The parametric form can now be read off:


											x_1 = 1+2t
											;
											x_2 = 1-2t+s
											;
											x_3 = 3+2t-6s.
										
										
					 				
					 				

Normal form:


					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 10 \\
											 12 \\
											 2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				x_{1} \\ x_{2}\\ x_{3}
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
											28
					 					

General form:


					 						5x_1
					 						+
											6x_2
											+
											x_3
											=
											14
					 					

Parametric form:


											x_1 = 1+2t
											;
											x_2 = 1-2t+s
											;
											x_3 = 3+2t-6s
										
															 					
					 				
					 			
					 		



Passing through A=(1,-1,6), B=(0,0,1), and C=(4,7,-11).


					 				

To find a normal vector \mbf{n} to the plane, we need two non-parallel vectors in the plane; for example, the two vectors


					 						\vect{BA}
					 						=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ -1\\ 6
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				0 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ -1\\ 5
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 		

and


					 						\vect{BC}
					 						=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				4 \\ 7\\ -11
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				0\\0\\1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				4 \\ 7\\ -12
								 			\end{bmatrix}								 			
					 					

would do. (If these two vectors had turned out to be parallel, then the three given points A, B, C would lie on a line, so they would not determine a plane.) A vector \mbf{n} which is orthogonal to both \vect{BA} and \vect{BC} is then given by their cross product:


					 						\mbf{n}
					 						=
					 						\vect{BA}
					 						\times
					 						\vect{BC}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 (-1) \cdot (-12) - 5 \cdot 7 \\
											 5 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot (-12) \\
											 1 \cdot 7 - 4\cdot (-1)
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 -23 \\
											 32 \\
											 11
											\end{bmatrix}
											.
					 					

The normal form, \mbf{n}\cdot\vect{BX}=0, is now explicitly given by


					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 -23 \\
											 32 \\
											 11
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				x_1 - 0 \\ x_2 - 0\\ x_3 - 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
											0
					 					

or equivalently


					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 -23 \\
											 32 \\
											 11
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\mbf{x}
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix}
											 -23 \\
											 32 \\
											 11
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				0 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			=
								 			11
								 			.
					 					

We get the general form by simply computing the dot product on both sides:


					 						-23x_1
					 						+
											32x_2
											+
											11x_3
											=
											11.
					 					

Lastly, we compute the parametric form by first giving the vector form:


					 						\mbf{x}
					 						=
					 						\vect{OB}
					 						+t\vect{BA}
					 						+s\vect{BC}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				0 \\ 0 \\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
					 						+t\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ -1\\ 5
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
					 						+s
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				4 \\ 7\\ -12
								 			\end{bmatrix}.
								 		

The parametric form can now be read off:


											x_1 =  t + 4s
											;
											x_2 = -t + 7s
											;
											x_3 =  1+ 5t - 12s.
										
					 				
					 				

Normal form:


					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 -23 \\
											 32 \\
											 11
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\mbf{x}
								 			=
								 			11
					 					

General form:


					 						-23x_1
					 						+
											32x_2
											+
											11x_3
											=
											11
					 					

Parametric form:


											x_1 =  t + 4s
											;
											x_2 = -t + 7s
											;
											x_3 = 1+ 5t - 12s
										
															 					
					 				
					 			
					 		



Passing through P=(2,-3,5) and parallel to the plane with general equation 3x_1-2x_2-x_3=0.


					 				
					 					Two planes are parallel if and only if they have the same normal vectors. Therefore, we should first find a  normal vector to the plane whose general equation is given: If we chose


					 						\mbf{n}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix},
										
										then the given general form is equivalent to


					 						\mbf{n}
					 						\cdot\mbf{x}
					 						=0,
										
										so \mbf{n} is indeed a normal vector. With this at hand, any point X=(x_1,x_2,x_3) on the plane whose normal form we are after can be described by \mbf{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0, or more explicitly:


											\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\mbf{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 2 \\
												 - 3 \\
												 5
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)
											=0
										
										To get the general form, we have to compute the dot product on the left-hand side and rearrange:


											3x_{1} - 2 x_{2} - x_{3}							
											= 7.
										
										For the vector form, we need two non-parallel vectors \mbf{u}, \mbf{v} which are orthogonal to \mbf{n}, i.e. they need to satisfy


											\mbf{u}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0
											\text{ and }
											\mbf{v}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0.
										
										For example,


											\mbf{u}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 -2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\text{ and }
											\mbf{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 3 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										
										work. Therefore, the vector equation of the plane is


											\mbf{x}
											=
											\vect{OP}
											+t\mbf{u}
											+s\mbf{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2\\-3\\5
											\end{bmatrix}
											+t\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 -2
											\end{bmatrix}
											+s\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 3 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										
										and so the parametric equations are


											x_1 =  2 +2s
											;
											x_2 =  -3 + t + 3s
											;
											x_3 =  5 -2t.
										
					 				
					 				

Normal form:


											\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 x_1 \\
											 x_2 \\
											 x_3
											\end{bmatrix}=
											7
										

General form:


											3x_{1} - 2 x_{2} - x_{3}							
											= 7
										

Parametric form:


											x_1 =  2 +2s
											;
											x_2 =  -3 + t + 3s
											;
											x_3 =  5 -2t
										
					 				
					 			
					 		



Passing through P=(3,0,-1) and parallel to the plane with equation 2x_1-x_2+x_3=3.


					 				
					 					Two planes are parallel if and only if they have the same normal vectors. Therefore, we should first find a  normal vector to the plane whose general equation is given: If we chose


					 						\mbf{n}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix},
										
										then the given general form is equivalent to


					 						\mbf{n}
					 						\cdot\mbf{x}
					 						=3,
										
										so \mbf{n} is indeed a normal vector. With this at hand, any point X=(x_1,x_2,x_3) on the plane whose normal form we are after can be described by \mbf{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0, or more explicitly:


											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\mbf{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\
												 0 \\
												 -1
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)
											=0
										
										To get the general form, we have to compute the dot product on the left-hand side and rearrange:


											2x_{1} - x_{2} + x_{3}							
											= 5.
										
										For the vector form, we need two non-parallel vectors \mbf{u}, \mbf{v} which are orthogonal to \mbf{n}, i.e. they need to satisfy


											\mbf{u}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0
											\text{ and }
											\mbf{v}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0.
										
										For example,


											\mbf{u}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\text{ and }
											\mbf{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 1 \\
											 2 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										
										work. Therefore, the vector equation of the plane is


											\mbf{x}
											=
											\vect{OP}
											+t\mbf{u}
											+s\mbf{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 0 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											+t\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											+s\begin{bmatrix}
											 1 \\
											 2 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										
										and so the parametric equations are


											x_1 = 3 + s
											;
											x_2 =  t+2s
											;
											x_3 =  -1+t.
										
					 				
					 				

Normal form:


											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\mbf{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\
												 0 \\
												 -1
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)
											=0
										

General form:


											2x_{1} - x_{2} + x_{3}							
											= 5
										

Parametric form:


											x_1 = 3 + s
											;
											x_2 =  t+2s
											;
											x_3 =  -1+t
										
					 				
					 			
					 		



Containing P=(3,0,-1) and the line 
					 			
					 				\mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
					 			
					 			


					 				
					 					Since the plane contains the line, it in particular contains the point Q=(0,0,2) (choose t=0 in the line equation). Since P is assumed to be in the plane, we conclude that the line that goes through Q=(0,0,2) and P, whose vector form is given by


							 				\mbf{x}  =
							 				\vect{OQ}
							 				+
							 				s\vect{QP}
							 				= 
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				,
							 			
							 			is also contained in the plane. Since this second line's directional vector is not parallel to the first line's directional vector, we conclude that the plane is spanned by those two directional vectors and thus has vector form


							 				\mbf{x} 
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
							 				+
							 				t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				.
							 			
							 			In particular, the parametric equations are


											x_1 = t + 3s
											;
											x_2 =  0
											;
											x_3 =  2+t-3s.
										
										We should remark that we can find a better set of parametric equations, namely


											x_1 = r
											;
											x_2 =  0
											;
											x_3 =  q,
										
										where r,q are any real numbers. To see this, just plug in the following values in :
										
											t = \frac{1}{2}(r+q-2)
											\text{ and }
											s = \frac{1}{6}(r-q+2)
											.
										
										We can find a normal vector \mbf{n} by taking the cross product of the two directional vectors:


											\mbf{n}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
							 				\times
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					0\cdot(-3) + 1\cdot 0 \\
							 					1\cdot 3 - 1\cdot (-3) \\
							 					1\cdot 0 - 0 \cdot 3
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				=							 				
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					0\\
							 					6 \\
							 					0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				.
										
										The normal equation of the plane is now given by \mbf{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0, or more explicitly:


											\begin{bmatrix}
							 					0\\
							 					6 \\
							 					0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\mbf{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\
												 0 \\
												 -1
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)=0
										
										and we get the general form by computing the dot product on the left-hand side and rearranging:


											6x_2
											=
											0,\text{ i.e. }
											x_2 = 0.
										
					 					
					 				

Normal form:


											\begin{bmatrix}
							 					0\\
							 					6 \\
							 					0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
