Each point which is equidistant from P=(0,1,-1) and Q=(2,-1,-3).


							 		
							 			A point X is equidistant from P and Q if and only if 
							 			
							 				\norm{\vect{OP}}^2
							 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}
							 				=
							 				\norm{\vect{OQ}}^2
							 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OQ}
							 				,
							 			
							 			see the argument in and  in particular.
							 			We compute with X=(x_1,x_2,x_3):
							 			
							 				
							 					\vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}
							 					=
							 					x_2 - x_3
							 				
							 				
							 					\vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OQ}
							 					=
							 					2x_1 - x_2 - 3x_3
							 				
							 				
							 					\norm{\vect{OP}}^2
							 					=
							 					0^2 + 1^2 +(-1)^2
							 					=
							 					2
							 				
							 				
							 					\norm{\vect{OQ}}^2
							 					=
							 					2^2 + (-1)^2 + (-3)^2
							 					=
							 					14,
							 				
							 			
							 			so that  becomes:
							 			
							 				
							 					\amp
								 				2
								 				- 2 (x_2 - x_3)
								 				=
								 				14
								 				- 2 (2x_1 - x_2 - 3x_3)
								 			
								 			
								 				\iff \amp
								 				2 (2x_1 - x_2 - 3x_3)
								 				- 2 (x_2 - x_3)
								 				=
								 				12
							 				
								 			
								 				\iff \amp
								 				4x_1 - 4x_2 - 4x_3
								 				=
								 				12,
								 			
							 			
							 			
							 			which is the general form of our plane equation. We can rewrite this to
							 			
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
												4 \\ -4 \\ - 4
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 \\
												x_2 \\
												x_3 
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											12,
										
										which is its normal form. Lastly, for the vector form, we need three points in the plane which do not lie on a line. Let us choose R_1= (3,0,0), R_2= (0, -3, 0), and R_3= (0,0,-3) which all satisfy the general equation. Now, the plane's vector equation is given by
										
											
												\mbf{x}
												\amp =
												\vect{OR_1}
												+
												t
												\vect{R_1 R_2}
												+
												s
												\vect{R_1 R_3}
											
												\amp	=
												\begin{bmatrix}
													3\\0\\0
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												t
												\begin{bmatrix}
													-3\\-3\\0
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												s
												\begin{bmatrix}
													-3\\0\\-3
												\end{bmatrix}
											
										
										which yields the parametric equations:
										
											x_1 = 3 -3t -3s
											;
											x_2 = -3t
											;
											x_3 = -3s
											.
										
							 		
							 		

Normal form:


