 (Source: , Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.12.) 
							In each case, calculate the distance from the point P to the line \ell, and find the point Q on \ell closest to P.
							 

	P=(3,2,-1), \ell \colon \mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}  
								

	P=(1,-1,3), \ell \colon \mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}

exercise.hint:
If a line \ell is given by the vector equation

	\mbf{x}
	=
	\mbf{a}
	+
	t\mbf{d}

and \mbf{p} is the position vector of a point P, then

	\mbf{q}
	:=
	\mbf{a} + \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}),

is the position vector of the point Q on \ell which is closest to the point P.

exercise.solution:
							According to , the formula for the distance between \ell and P is given by
							
								\operatorname{dist}
								(\ell, P) = 
								\norm{(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}) - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a})},
							
							where \mbf{a} is a point on the line and \mathbf{d} is a direction vector of the line. We now only have to plug in the values for the two situations:
							 

 
								For the given \ell, we have
								
									\mbf{a} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix},
									\mbf{d} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix},
									\text{ and }
									\mbf{p} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								
								so that
								
									\mbf{v}
									:=
									\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
									-
									\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ -4 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								
								We compute
								
									
										\mathbf{v} \cdot  \mathbf{d}
										\amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ -4 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									
									
										\amp =
										\bigl(1\cdot 3 + 1 \cdot (-1) + (-4)\cdot (-2)\bigr)
										=10.
									
								
								and
								
									\mbf{d}\cdot \mbf{d}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									3^2 + (-1)^2 + (-2)^2
									=
									14,
								
								so that (using )
								
									\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}
									=
									\left(
										\frac{\mbf{d}\cdot \mbf{v}}{\mbf{d}\cdot \mbf{d}}
									\right)
									\mbf{d}
									=
									\tfrac{10}{14}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								
								Therefore,
								
									
										\operatorname{dist}
										(\ell, P) 
										\amp =
										\norm{\mathbf{v} - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}}
										=
										\norm{
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ -4 \end{bmatrix}
											-
											\tfrac{10}{14}
											\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}}
									
									
										\amp = 
										\norm{\tfrac{1}{14}\begin{bmatrix} -16 \\ 24 \\ -36 \end{bmatrix}}
									
									
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{ \left(\tfrac{-16}{14}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{24}{14}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{-36}{14}\right)^2}
									
									
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{\tfrac{152}{14}}.
									
								
								Next, for the point Q on \ell which has distance \sqrt{\tfrac{152}{14}} from P, we use : we need
								
									\mbf{q}
									:=
									\mbf{a} + \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + \tfrac{10}{14}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\tfrac{1}{14}\begin{bmatrix} 58 \\ 4\\ 22 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								
								so that Q= (\tfrac{29}{7}, \tfrac{2}{7}, \tfrac{11}{7}).
								


								P=(1,-1,3), \ell \colon \mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}  
								For the given \ell, we have
								
									\mbf{a} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix},
									\mbf{d} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix},
									\text{ and }
									\mbf{p} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								
								so that
								
									\mbf{v}
									:=
									\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
									-
									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								
								We compute
								
									
										\mathbf{v} \cdot  \mathbf{d}
										\amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
										\cdot
										\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									
									
										\amp =
										\bigl(0\cdot 3 + (-1) \cdot 1 + 4\cdot 4\bigr)
										=15.
									
								
								and
								
									\mbf{d}\cdot \mbf{d}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									3^2 + 1^2 + 4^2
									=
									26,
								
								so that (using )
								
									\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}
									=
									\left(
										\frac{\mbf{d}\cdot \mbf{v}}{\mbf{d}\cdot \mbf{d}}
									\right)
									\mbf{d}
									=
									\tfrac{15}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								
								Therefore,
								
									
										\operatorname{dist}
										(\ell, P) 
										\amp =
										\norm{\mathbf{v} - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}}
										=
										\norm{
											\begin{bmatrix}  0 \\ -1\\ 4  \end{bmatrix}
											-
											\tfrac{15}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
										}
									
									
										\amp = 
										\norm{\tfrac{1}{26}\begin{bmatrix} -45 \\ -41 \\ 44 \end{bmatrix}}
									
									
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{ \left(\tfrac{-45}{26}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{-41}{26}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{44}{26}\right)^2}
									
									
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{\tfrac{217}{26}}.
									
								
								Next, for the point Q on \ell which has distance \sqrt{\tfrac{217}{26}} from P, we use : we need
								
									\mbf{q}
									:=
									\mbf{a} + \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 0\\ -1  \end{bmatrix}
									+
									\tfrac{15}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\tfrac{1}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 71 \\ 15\\ 34 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								
								so that Q= (\tfrac{71}{26}, \tfrac{15}{26}, \tfrac{34}{26}).

							According to , we only need to find a point A on the plane and a normal vector \mbf{n} to the plane.
							 

 For the plane with general equation 5x_1+x_2+x_3 =1, we can choose 
						 		\mbf{n} = \begin{bmatrix}
									5\\
									1\\
									1
								\end{bmatrix}
								\text{ and }
