exercise.statement:

 (Source: , Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.23.) 
							Find the shortest distance between the following pairs of parallel lines.
						 	 

	\ell_1\colon\mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}   and 
						 		\ell_2\colon\mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}  
						 		

	\ell_1\colon\mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}   and 
						 	\ell_1\colon\mbf{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}

exercise.hint:
Find a normal vector \mbf{n}_1 resp. \mbf{n}_2 for each of the planes. Using the Cosine Formula, compute the angle \theta=\sphericalangle (\mbf{n}_1, \mbf{n}_2) between these vectors. Then,

	\sphericalangle (\mathcal{P}_1, \mathcal{P}_2)
	=
	\left\{
		\begin{array}{lc}
			\theta \amp \text{ if } 0 \leq \theta \leq \tfrac{\pi}{2}\\
			\pi - \theta \amp \text{ if } \tfrac{\pi}{2} \leq \theta \leq \pi \\
		\end{array}
	\right.

exercise.solution:
A normal vector to \mathcal{P}_1 resp. \mathcal{P}_2 is given by

	\mbf{n}_1
	=
	\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
	\text{ resp. }
	\mbf{n}_2
	=
	\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
	.
 
According to the Cosine Formula, the angle between \mbf{n}_1 and \mbf{n}_2 is the number \theta that satisfies

	\cos (\theta)
	=
	\frac{ \mbf{n}_1\cdot \mbf{n}_2}{ \norm{\mbf{n}_1}\cdot \norm{\mbf{n}_2}}
	,

so we compute:

	
		\mbf{n}_1\cdot \mbf{n}_2
		\amp =
		1\cdot 2 + 1\cdot 1 + 0\cdot (-1) = 3
	
	
		\norm{\mbf{n}_1}
		\amp =
		\sqrt{ 1^2 + 1^2 + 0^2}
		=
		\sqrt{2}
	
	
		\norm{\mbf{n}_1}
		\amp =
		\sqrt{ 2^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2}
		=
		\sqrt{6},
	

so that

	\cos (\theta)
	=
	\frac{ 3}{ \sqrt{2}\cdot \sqrt{6}}
	=
	\frac{ 3}{\sqrt{12}}
	,
	\text{ i.e. }
	\sphericalangle (\mathcal{P}_1, \mathcal{P}_2)
	=
	\theta = \tfrac{\pi}{6}
	.

