exercise.statement:

(Source:  in Section 1.2, Exercise 1.2.1.)
							Which of the following matrices are in reduced-echelon form?  Which are in row-echelon form?		
							


									\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp  -1 \amp  2\\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \end{bmatrix}
								


									\begin{bmatrix} 2\amp  1 \amp  -1 \amp  3 \\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \end{bmatrix}
								


									\begin{bmatrix}1\amp  -2 \amp  3 \amp  5 \\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \end{bmatrix}
								


									\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  3 \amp  1 \\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  1\\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \end{bmatrix}
								


									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp  1 \\ 0 \amp  1\end{bmatrix}
								


									\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \\  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \\  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \end{bmatrix}


 (Source: , Section 1.2, Exercise 1.2.20.) 
							Row reduce the following matrix to obtain the row-echelon form. Then continue to obtain the reduced row-echelon form.
		 
							
								\begin{bmatrix}
									2 \amp  -1 \amp  3 \amp  -1  \\ 1 \amp  0 \amp  2 \amp  1 \\  1 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  -2 
								\end{bmatrix}

exercise.solution:
To find out if there is a common point of intersection we want to find out if the three given equations have a simultaneous solution.  We therefore turn the equations into an augmented matrix and row reduce:

	\matr{rr|r}{1\amp 2\amp 1\\2\amp -1\amp 1\\4\amp 3\amp 3}
	\to \matr{rr|r}{1\amp 2\amp 1 \\ 0 \amp  -5 \amp  -1 \\ 0 \amp  -5 \amp  -1} 
	\to \matr{rr|r}{1 \amp  0 \amp  \frac{3}{5} \\ 0 \amp  1 \amp  \frac{1}{5} \\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0}

The row reduced form tells us that there is a solution to this system, and that the only solution is x=\frac{3}{5}, y = \frac{1}{5}.  Therefore the three given lines do have a common point of intersection, and that point is \left(\frac{3}{5}, \frac{1}{5}\right).

